# Project: Jack String Library & Custom Assembler Pipeline

## 📌 Project Overview
[cite_start]This repository contains the implementation for a three-part systems architecture project[cite: 3, 4, 6]. [cite_start]The objective is to build foundational OS-level string manipulation functions in Jack [cite: 9][cite_start], develop a custom general-purpose assembler [cite: 4][cite_start], and integrate the compiled machine code directly into simulated hardware[cite: 6, 7].

---

## 🚀 Phase 1: String Library Implementation (Jack)
[cite_start]**Objective:** Implement core string manipulation functions in the Jack programming language and verify them via simulation[cite: 3, 9].

### Tasks:
- [ ] [cite_start]**Implement `String.setCharAt(j, c)`:** Set the *j*-th character of the string to the given character *c*[cite: 9].
- [ ] [cite_start]**Implement `String.appendChar(c)`:** Append character *c* to the end of the string, handling length tracking, and return the updated string[cite: 9].
- [ ] [cite_start]**Implement `String.eraseLastChar()`:** Erase the last character from the string and update the length pointer[cite: 9].
- [ ] [cite_start]**Implement `String.intValue()`:** Parse the string and return its integer value, breaking the loop at the first non-numeric character[cite: 9].
- [ ] [cite_start]**Compilation:** Compile the `String.jack` and a test `Main.jack` file using the standard Jack Compiler[cite: 3].
- [ ] [cite_start]**Simulation:** Load the generated `.vm` files into the VM Emulator and successfully execute the test cases[cite: 3].

---

## ⚙️ Phase 2: Custom General-Purpose Assembler
[cite_start]**Objective:** Write a custom assembler from scratch to translate Hack assembly language (`.asm`) into 16-bit machine code (`.hack`)[cite: 4].

[cite_start]*Note: This must be a custom-developed tool, entirely independent of the assembler supplied with the course materials[cite: 5].*

### Tasks:
- [ ] [cite_start]**Parser Development:** Build a parser to strip whitespaces, ignore comments, and isolate raw instructions[cite: 4].
- [ ] **Pass 1 (Symbol Resolution):** Scan the assembly code to identify all label declarations (e.g., `(LOOP)`) and store them in a Symbol Table with their corresponding instruction ROM addresses.
- [ ] **Pass 2 (Translation):** - Translate A-instructions (`@value` or `@symbol`) into 16-bit binary.
  - Translate C-instructions (`dest=comp;jump`) into their corresponding 16-bit binary operational codes.
- [ ] [cite_start]**Verification:** Run test `.asm` files through both this custom assembler and the official Nand2tetris assembler[cite: 4]. Verify that the output `.hack` files match bit-for-bit.

---

## 🛠️ Phase 3: Hardware Architecture Integration
[cite_start]**Objective:** Load the generated machine code into memory and execute it on the CPU hardware architecture[cite: 6, 7].

### Tasks:
- [ ] [cite_start]**Memory Loading:** Dump the 16-bit machine code (`.hack` files) generated by the custom assembler directly into `RAM.hdl`[cite: 6].
- [ ] [cite_start]**Bus Routing:** Design and verify the architecture connections[cite: 7]. [cite_start]Ensure that the address buses and data buses are correctly wired between the CPU, Instruction Memory, and Data Memory during execution[cite: 8].
- [ ] [cite_start]**Execution:** Run the hardware simulator and verify that the CPU correctly fetches, decodes, and executes the instructions loaded in RAM[cite: 6, 8].
